entry.title: Disable lazy loading for the new headless mode
entry.content:
This CL adds the command-line switch --disable-lazy-loading to Chrome,

which allows users to disable lazy loading of images.

When this switch is present, lazy loading is disabled regardless of

other conditions. Additionally, the switch is appended to the new

headless mode to disable lazy loading, similar to the behavior

of the old headless mode.



Bug: 1408885

entry.title: Check that universal buckets are empty after default style updates
entry.content:
We only used to check for empty buckets after the initialization, not

after adding on-demand rules.



Some of the on-demand sheets contain universal bucket rules. DCHECK

the current counts so that when more universal bucket rules are added,

they are added consciously.



RuleSets that are aggregated from others like for printing and forced

colors may have different bucket counts based on which combinations of

element types rules have been ensured from, so those are not checked.

entry.title: [WebUI] Migrate ProximityAuthUI to WebUIConfig
entry.content:
Context:



Currently WebUI properties, e.g. CSPs, requesting schemes, host, mojo,

etc. are stored in WebUIControllers themselves or in separate lists

like IsWebUIAllowedToMakeNetworkRequests. The lifetime of a

WebUIController is bound to the frame, which makes it hard to use for

some use cases where the WebUIController hasn't been created yet. A

non-dynamically allocated class where clients could query a WebUI's

properties would be easier to use and audit.



WebUIConfig is a class that stores properties of WebUIs. For now the

properties are 1. the WebUI's origin, 2. if the WebUI is enabled,

and 3. GetURLDataSource() method for service worker initialization.

In the future this class could include information like CSPs, if we

should enable Mojo, if we should enable chrome.send(), if we should

allow network requests, URLDataSource, etc.



Bug: 1317510

entry.title: Resend update-engine request when IDLE signal is received
entry.content:
A request to update will always receive a non-IDLE signal response,

followed by IDLE once the engine is ready to receive the next request.

If we receive IDLE before we have received non-IDLE, then we should

resend the request. Either (1) our request was sent while another

request was in-progress, or (2) we received a prior signal just before

sending our request. For (1), we must resend, for (2) it is safe to do

so since the duplicate request will be ignored if the first is still

in-progress, or a subsequent request to update will not cause any

problem.



The associated bug shows that tests were failing when a DLC install

request is sent prior to the update since the engine is already busy

and ignores the update request. This CL now causes chrome to resend

the update request once the engine goes back to idle.



Bug: b/279088859

entry.title: visual-debugger: Support buffer dumping with videos on Windows
entry.content:
Pages with YUV videos cause two issues with the Visual Debugger GPU

texture dumping code:

- Video overlays on Windows cause the root surface to render using

DComp surfaces. The SI backing for these surfaces set up a special

GLSurface that must be alive during the SkiaRepresentation write

access. AttemptDebuggerBufferCapture changes the current context,

which trips an assertion in our SI representation's EndWrite.

- Non-multi-planar SI for YUV textures do not set a color space for

each of the SI planes. An invalid gfx::ColorSpace turns into a

nullptr SkColorSpace, which AttemptDebuggerBufferCapture attempts

to dereference unconditionally.
